<taxonomicName id="96DA4D3D9D38FF9FFCCC8802FC4D8B14" authorityName="Blume" authorityYear="1850" box="[799,928,1060,1084]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nothofagaceae" genus="Nothofagus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63AEEAAC9D38FF9FFCCC8802FC4D8B14" box="[799,928,1060,1084]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Nothofagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forests of the Nahuel Huapi National Park of 
<collectingRegion id="931EF85C9D38FF9FFF44886FFE858B49" box="[151,360,1096,1121]" country="Argentina" name="Neuquen" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Neuquen province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="29CD762E9D38FF9FFEA0886EFE0F8B49" box="[371,482,1096,1121]" name="Argentina" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="C9E12A3B9D38FF9FFE21886EFDA88B49" box="[498,581,1096,1121]" captionStart="FIGURE 35" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1234,1256]" captionTargetBox="[267,1325,252,1118]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[205,1396,196,1194]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 35. Map of Argentine and Chilean Patagonia with distribution records of: Austrohelea shannoni (Wirth &amp; Blanton), green circles. Austrohelea sirii n. sp., yellow triangles. Austrohelea spinosa n. sp., red diamonds." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/806131/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516536BE9D38FF9FFF14884AFCC98BD9" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1589]" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis id="63AEEAAC9D38FF9FFF14884AFDBE8BAD" bold="true" box="[199,595,1132,1157]" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Derivation of the specific epithet.</emphasis>
We are pleased to name this new species after our colleague Augusto Siri, at the Instituto de Limnología “Dr. Raúl A. Ringuelet”, La Plata, 
<collectingCountry id="29CD762E9D38FF9FFC7E88B6FBF28B81" box="[941,1055,1168,1193]" name="Argentina" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, in recognition of his important contributions to the taxonomy of 
<taxonomicName id="96DA4D3D9D38FF9FFDF28892FD2C8BE5" authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1834" box="[545,705,1204,1229]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chironomidae</taxonomicName>
in the Neotropical Region, and for his valuable collections of 
<taxonomicName id="96DA4D3D9D38FF9FFF4488FEFEBB8BD9" authorityName="Newman" authorityYear="1834" box="[151,342,1240,1265]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ceratopogonidae</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="29CD762E9D38FF9FFE4888FEFDE78BD9" box="[411,522,1240,1265]" name="Argentina" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Argentina</collectingCountry>
during the past 10 years.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="19C065359D38FF9FFF1488DAFB8F891D" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="516536BE9D38FF9FFF1488DAFAB68A8D" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1589]" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis id="63AEEAAC9D38FF9FFF1488DAFEA18A3D" bold="true" box="[199,332,1276,1301]" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">Discussion.</emphasis>
This new species is readily distinguished from its Neotropical congeners by its small size and the well-defined sensory pit on palpal segment 3. The male gonocoxite is very short, stout and lacks a basomesal tubercle; the gonostylus is much longer than the gonocoxite; and, the aedeagus is small, lightly sclerotized with a very low slightly concave basal arch, the apex is rounded and lacks a distal extension. The female wing membrane has dense, coarse macrotrichia and the spermathecae are pyriform, unequal, with short, broad truncate necks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="516536BE9D38FF9FFF148997FB8F891D" blockId="8.[151,1437,151,1589]" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">
Two other species from Australasia also have a sensory pit on palpal segment 3. In his original description of 
<taxonomicName id="96DA4D3D9D38FF9FFF4489F3FEFC8AC4" authorityName="Macfie" authorityYear="1932" baseAuthorityName="Macfie" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[151,273,1493,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Austrohelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tonnoiri">
<emphasis id="63AEEAAC9D38FF9FFF4489F3FF458AC4" box="[151,168,1493,1516]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="63AEEAAC9D38FF9FFF6489F3FEFC8AC4" box="[183,273,1493,1516]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">tonnoiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="29CD762E9D38FF9FFE8B89F3FE1F8AC5" box="[344,498,1492,1517]" name="New Zealand" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="354B4B4F9D38FF9FFE2D89F2FD4D8AC5" author="Macfie" box="[510,672,1492,1517]" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" refString="Macfie, J. W. S. (1932) New Zealand biting midges (Diptera, Ceratopogonidae). Annals of Tropical Medicine and Parasitology, 26, 23 - 53." type="journal article" year="1932">Macfie (1932)</bibRefCitation>
stated “…third (palpal segment) not inflated, bearing sensory hairs on a depressed area on apical third” and 
<bibRefCitation id="354B4B4F9D38FF9FFDBA89DEFCC78939" author="Tokunaga" box="[617,810,1528,1553]" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" refString="Tokunaga, M. (1964) Insects of Campbell Island. Diptera: Ceratopogonidae. Pacific Insects Monograph, 7, 289 - 291." type="journal article" year="1964">Tokunaga (1964)</bibRefCitation>
noted for 
<taxonomicName id="96DA4D3D9D38FF9FFC7189DFFB8F8938" authorityName="Tokunaga" authorityYear="1964" baseAuthorityName="Tokunaga" baseAuthorityYear="1964" box="[930,1122,1528,1552]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Austrohelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="263" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="campbellensis">
<emphasis id="63AEEAAC9D38FF9FFC7189DFFC5E8938" box="[930,947,1529,1552]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="63AEEAAC9D38FF9FFC1089DEFB8F8938" box="[963,1122,1528,1552]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="263">campbellensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Campbell Island, that palpal segment 3 is “…slightly thickened, with very small sensory pore on apical 1/3.”
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
